===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|nautical|lang=en}} A tool used to moor a [[vessel]] to the bottom of a sea or river to resist movement.
## Formerly a vessel would differentiate amongst the anchors carried as ''waist anchor'', ''best bower'', ''bower'', ''stream'' and ''kedge'' anchors, depending on purpose and, to a great extent, on mass and size of the anchor. Modern usage is ''storm anchor'' for the heaviest anchor with the longest rode, ''best bower'' or simply ''bower'' for the most commonly used anchor deployed from the [[bow]], and ''stream'' or ''lunch hook'' for a small, light anchor used for temporary moorage and often deployed from the [[stern]].
## {{context|nautical|lang=en}} An [[iron]] [[device]] so shaped as to [[grip]] the bottom and hold a vessel at her berth by the chain or rope attached. (FM 55-501).
# {{context|nautical|lang=en}} Generic term to refer to the combined anchoring gear (anchor, [[rode]], and [[fittings]] such as [[bitts]], [[cat]], and [[windlass]].)
# A fixed point, especially materials or tools used to [[affix]] something at that point.
# {{context|Internet|lang=en}} A marked point in a [[document]] that can be the [[target]] of a [[hyperlink]].
# {{context|television|lang=en}} An [[anchorman]] or [[anchorwoman]].
# {{context|athletics|lang=en}} The final runner in a [[relay race]].
# A [[superstore]] or other facility that serves as a [[focus]] to bring customers into an area.
#* '''2006''', ''Planning: For the Natural and Built Environment'' (issues 1650-1666, page 15)
#*: Supermarkets have also had to adjust. Tesco, Sainsbury's and Asda have put a much greater emphasis on developing smaller high street stores or becoming '''anchors''' for mixed-used regeneration schemes {{...}}

